It is more of a wooded area than a garden, but any patch of greenery is welcome. In 1683, the construction of the Minimes convent was completed here, which was closed in 1790. It was in 1823 that the old buildings of the convent, then national property acquired by the Municipality of Paris, were transformed into a gendarmerie known as the “Minimes Barracks”. In 2019, the function of this island changes. The buildings are restructured to accommodate social housing and a nursery. The interior courtyard is open and planted with plants. It partly becomes a public garden and two spaces at the ends are made available to residents. Planters are installed along the edges and trees are planted in the center in the spirit of the garden of the old cloister.

The garden is a little cold and impersonal but that is also what gives it a certain particularity. Isolated from the street, we appreciate the calm of a stopover. Dogs on a leash can “visit” the regularly aligned tree plantation.
It's becoming unmanageable, you can't even walk your little 5kg dog there for 10 minutes in the morning and let him run around a little. The police come to do rounds there several times a week
Pretty, well-hidden garden just a stone's throw from Place des Vosges

Given its minerality, this garden is more like a courtyard than a real green space. There are certainly trees, but its surface is mainly paved, with little grass and shrubs; everything is orderly and symmetrical. A sober courtyard in a superbly renovated convent and very elegant in its architecture. A lawn and benches would not have been too much (to sit somewhere other than on a side wall).

We pinch ourselves when discovering that this courtyard can be described as a “garden”. It is not bad, but it refers to a very 20th century conception where the idea of ​​climate change struggled to be recognized. While the City of Paris is launching a reflection on de-bitumen, to de-waterproof schoolyards, it is creating an all-mineral garden. The trees are not everything, nor are the planters on either side, going against current needs, it is a return to the future that this courtyard offers.

Pleasant place to relax and read a book far from the hustle and bustle of Place des Vosges. Very graphic atmosphere and perhaps too refined and concrete for my taste...very much like the renovation work carried out in Paris since the 2000s. Despite these regrets, the rehabilitation of the place remains pleasant and of high quality .

Replaces an old gendarmerie barracks, a somewhat mineral square, like all 3rd millennium constructions, but on the side there is a café restaurant whose staff is disabled, very good initiative, magnificent.
A few trees surrounded by concrete, like the Place de la Bastille... Very 90s, all of this while a city like Paris urgently needs real green spaces that reduce pollution and provide heat!
